          </p>
          <p>
            <Image src="/Solid_Mechanics/TransverseShear-Figures/ThinWalledMembers.png" width=""></Image>  
 
            The variation of shear flow across the section depends only on the variation of the first moment.
           <DisplayEquation equation="q = \\tau t = \\frac{VQ}{I}\\" />
           
           <Image src="/Solid_Mechanics/TransverseShear-Figures/rectThinWallShearFlow.png" width=""></Image> 
            For a box beam, q grows symmetrically. From the edge to where the beam becomes hollow, the flow increases linearly and from where it becomes hollow to the neutral axis, the flow increases parabolically.
           
            <Image src="/Solid_Mechanics/TransverseShear-Figures/IbeamShearFlow.png" width=""></Image> 
             For a wide-flange beam, the shear flow increases symmetrically on top from the end to the neutral axis in the y direction, and on the side increases from the flanges to the neutral axes.
           
             <Image src="/Solid_Mechanics/TransverseShear-Figures/UchannelShearFlow.png" width=""></Image> 
             For a u-channel beam, the shear flow increases linearly on the sides from the edge to the base, and on the base it increases from the sides to the neutral axis.

          </p>
